<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Grace Byron, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668087862" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Herculine</em> </a></strong><br />
<strong>S&amp;S/Saga Press, October 7</strong></p>
<p>A â€œparanoid, self-annihilatingâ€ horror debut that the author elevator-pitched as a â€œtrans girl <em>Buffy</em>â€? Yes! Iâ€™m excited for this one, especially since Iâ€™m already a fan of Byronâ€™s fantastic reviews and longform, in particular her piece for<em> The Nation</em> on a trans vegan cult obsessed with AI, which feels like it may have partially inspired this novel. <em>Herculine</em> follows a woman who escapes NYC and her demons, both literal and figurative, to an all-trans girl commune in Indiana. Naturally, things get a little wild at the rural commune, and our protagonist has to unravel frightening mysteries and contend with â€œdisemboweled pigs, cultlike psychosexual rituals, and the horrors of communal breakfast.â€Â <em>â€“JF, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/">as recommended in our second-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
