<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Zefyr Lisowski, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063413993" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Uncanny Valley Girls: Essays on Horror, Survival, and Love</em> </a></strong><br />
<strong>Harper Perennial, October 7</strong></p>
<p>I love the pairing of personal narrative with film criticism, and I thought Lisowskiâ€™s <em>Girl Work</em> was excellent. Horror is horrific in part because it brings humans a little too close to ourselves for comfort. It holds a mirror to the parts of us we donâ€™t want to see. But it can also act as a space for solace and interpretation for those who love it, and that seemingly contradictory place is what excites me about these essays.Â <em>â€“Oliver Scialdone, Community Editor, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/">as recommended in our second-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
